#Data visualization 
#automatic data 
qplot (data=data.final, temp)#data seem right-skewed

qplot (data=data.final, Intensity)#data looks exponential, but we have to explore more
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

#let's see if temperature and light intensity are correlated 
qplot(data= data.final, temp, Intensity, geom = c ("point", "smooth")) + xlab("Temperature (°F)") + ylab ("Light Intensity (lum/ft²)")+ theme_classic()+ theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12))#there seems to be a positive correlation
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

#graph a boxplot for temperature, and light per type of cover and shape
ggplot(data.final, aes(as.factor(cover.type), Intensity, fill= shape)) + geom_boxplot() + xlab("Cover Type (% light permeability)") + ylab ("Temperature (°F)")+ theme_classic()+ theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12))#boxplots overalp, prehaps significanlty different

ggplot(data.final, aes(as.factor(shelter.open), temp, fill= as.character(cover.type))) + geom_boxplot() + xlab("Treatment") + ylab ("Temperature (°F)")+ theme_classic()+ theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12))

ggplot(data.final, aes(as.factor(shelter.open), Intensity, fill= as.character(cover.type))) + geom_boxplot() + xlab("Treatment") + ylab ("Light Intensity (lum/ft²)")+ theme_classic()+ theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12))

#let's see if mean daily temperature and light varies by timeblock 
ggplot(data=data.final, aes(timeblock, temp)) + geom_boxplot(aes(fill=shape))+ ylab("Temperature (°F)")+ xlab("Timeblock")+  theme_classic()+ theme(axis.text=element_text(size=12))#boxplot overlapp, again two replicates of treatment are present....

#EDA
#explore normality 
#can't do Shapiro-Wilk dataset too large 
library(ggpubr)

ggqqplot(data.final$temp)#data is positively(right) skewed, Gaussian  

hist(data.final$temp) 

ggqqplot(data.final$Intensity)#data looks exponential or poisson 

hist(data.final$Intensity)

#neither intensity nor temperature follow a normal distribution
#Models
cor.test(data.final$temp, data.final$Intensity, method= "kendall")
## 
##  Kendall's rank correlation tau
## 
## data:  data.final$temp and data.final$Intensity
## z = 84.177, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true tau is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       tau 
## 0.5825685
ggscatter(data.final, x="temp", y="Intensity", add= "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, cor.coef = TRUE, method="kendall", xlab = "Temperature (°F)", ylab = "Light Intensity (lum/ft²)")#temperature and light are positively correlated (p-value<0.05)
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: method

#explore temperature more 
#perform a two-way anova
res.aov2 <- aov(temp~cover.type*shape, data = data.final)
summary (res.aov2)
##                     Df  Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## cover.type           1   19477   19477  44.074 3.32e-11 ***
## shape                2    4322    2161   4.890  0.00754 ** 
## cover.type:shape     1    1406    1406   3.182  0.07447 .  
## Residuals        10405 4598037     442                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#no signficant difference between shapes when it comes to temperature, but there is a difference in type of cover when it comes to temperature (p=0.00137<0.01)

#run a non-parametric post-hoc to make sure above is true
kruskal.test(temp ~ cover.type, data = data.final)# p-value<0.05
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  temp by cover.type
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 19.209, df = 3, p-value = 0.0002475
pairwise.wilcox.test(data.final$temp, data.final$cover.type)
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Wilcoxon rank sum test 
## 
## data:  data.final$temp and data.final$cover.type 
## 
##    0      15     50    
## 15 0.2884 -      -     
## 50 0.0439 0.0015 -     
## 90 0.0319 0.0010 0.7598
## 
## P value adjustment method: holm
#there is a sig. difference between 50% and 15% (p=0.0013), and between 90% and 50% (p=0.0115)

res.aov3 <- aov(temp~cover.type*shape+timeblock, data = data.final)

#Summary 
###1. The intensity of sunlight and temperature are positively correlated.(R=0.61, p-value= <2.2e-16)
###2. Shape does significanly affect the temperature of canopy.
###3. The percentage of cover used significantly affects temperature.
###3. there is a signicant difference between 50% and 15% cover (p-value=0.0013), and between 90% and 50% (p-value=0.0115), cover when it comes to temperature.
